“ Tafi has a decimal numeral system. The counting forms of cardinal numbers are different from the form they take in attributive position. In the counting form, the words for six, seven, and nine have zero prefix while the others have prefixes which are vowels. The multiples of ten, i.e., twenty, thirty, etc. are formed by prefixing either the root or the stem of the numbers ‘one’ to ‘nine’ with the prefix áf-,  and the quantifier prefix t-, yielding áf-t- followed by the vowel /a/ or /e/ depending on the ATR value of the stem except for the words for ‘thirty’ and ‘fifty’. The word for ‘thirty’ is formed by prefixing áf- followed by two vowels /aa/ to the root of three whereas for ‘fifty’, it is formed by prefixing áf- followed by the vowel /e/ to the form ‘five’, that is, the prefix together with the root. The words alafá ‘hundred’ and akpé ‘thousand’ are borrowed words from Ewe whereas that for ‘million’ míliɔis borrowed from English

I numeri della lingua evé offrono speciale interesse, rivelando un sistema di numerazione diversissimo dal nostro, perchè i numeri che servono di base o di fondamento agli altri numeri non sono, come nelle nostre lingue, le unità, il cento etc., ma il 20 (etcì), il 40 (ékka,ka) l’80 (ka-vé), il 120 (katon), il 160 (kanné) il 200 (kató), il 2000 (yotd). Così p. es. l’800 è Teatri cioè ka 40, e tri 20; il 4000 è yo-tu-ve, cioè yo-tu 2000, e ve, due, due volte. Molti sono i numeri ottenuti colla sottrazione dai numeri più elevati. Cosi 190 si dice èi too to-le ka-to me lett. « dieci meno di due cento». L’elemento di (Henr. 225 idi, che entra in parecchi numeri, propriamente designa una piccola conchiglia (cypraea cauri»), che ora serve per ornamento delle vesti degli indigeni, ma un tempo sei viva come moneta (1). Ecco ora la nostra lista di numeri cardinali, che presenta qua e là qualche divergenza di fronte a quella di Henr. (pp. 33, 34), contenendo alcune forme proprie dell’Gen, e, in genere, più ricco materiale. Nè ci sembra il caso di semplificarla, atteso il grande interesse, che desta la formazione dei numeri. The numbers of the Evé language offer special interest, revealing a a numbering system very different from ours, because the numbers that serve as the basis or foundation for the other numbers are not, as in our languages, the units, the hundred etc, but the 20 (etcì), the 40 (ékka,ka) the 80 (ka-vé), the 120 (katon), the 160 (kanné) the 200 (kató), the 2000 (yotd). Thus e.g. the 800 is Teatri viz. ka 40, and tri 20; the 4000 is yo-tu-ve, i.e. yo-tu 2000, and ve, two, two times. Many are the numbers obtained by subtraction from the numbers higher. Thus 190 is said èi too to-le ka-to me lett. “ ten minus than two hundred.” The element of (Henr. 225 idi, which goes into several numbers, properly designates a small shell (cypraea cauri"), which now serves as adornment for the clothing of the natives, but once you are alive as a coin (1). Here now is our list of cardinal numbers, which has here and there some divergence from that of Henr. (pp. 33, 34), containing some forms peculiar to the Gen, and, in general, richer material. Nor does it seem to us the case to simplify it, given the great interest, which arouses the formation of the numbers."

A noun followed by a numeral adjective remains in the singular: mi katâ novi yutsu wuieve mienye (We are twelve brothers in all). But if the adjective is followed by the article a, the adjective becomes plural: Viyutsu wuieveawo (the twelve sons). So many things or objects are translated by ame (man), which is usually preceded by the pronoun wo (man). preceded by the pronoun wo (them). E.g.: Tè le mia sia? The complex numeral làfāā léé ‘1,000,000’ is formed by a juxtaposition of the numeral làfāā ‘1,000’ with a special marker léé for which we have no etymology so far. Numerals for tens of millions and, presumably, higher numerical values can be built by a juxtaposition of the complex base làfāā léé ‘1,000,000’ with a multiplicand, for example, làfāā léé tā ‘3,000,000’.

cardinal numbers for enumeration and cardinal numbers for designation. Enumeration is the act of stating numbers it is an abstract operation, whereas designating which consists in expressing a quantity is a concrete a concrete operation, with an obligatory reference. In the operations of enumeration and designation two morphemes need to be taken into account morphemes that enable numbers to be associated to each other. These two morphemes are not involved in the constitution of the first 9 numbers and the immediately related to them, i.e. from 1 to 9 and 10 to 19.

wi - twenty, vɔ̀n most likely and one. 21-29 are formed with wi- ‘twenty’, von (meaning unknown) and the short form of a number 1-9. Examples of this are wivbn4eka 21 and wivonaton 25. The first tone of the word representing the units changes from H to L in this environment. Furthermore, the final syllable of wivonaton 25 surfaces with a H tone while L would be expected.

Numbers from 30-49 begin with a decimal base, egban ‘thirty’ or eka ‘forty’, which can then be followed by xd ‘plus’ (in other contexts ‘to hit’) and the short form of a number 1-10. Examples of this are egban xo ene 34 and eka xo adm 46.
The number system begins to behave somewhat like a base-40 system at 40, but there are elements of base-20 and base-10 systems clearly visible.

Other numbers from 41-999T (inclusive) are formed in two ways, depending upon the value of the units place. If the unit’s digit is between one and seven (inclusive), then the number is formed by the multiple of ten followed by xd and the units. For example, sixty-two is eka xo ewi xo eve (forty plus twenty plus two) and seventy-four is eka xd ewi xd ewo xd ene (forty plus twenty plus ten plus four). If the unit5s place is eight or nine, then like 18 and 19, the structure is ‘one/two leaves in . . . 5, for example eve to le eka xo ewi me (two leaves in forty plus ten).
